Looking at the code fragments, I can see that Hexi provides endianness conversion utilities. Based on the patterns shown in the fragments, here's the implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/endian.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <bit>

template<std::endian from, std::endian to, typename T>
T convert_endianness(T value) {
    if constexpr (from == to) {
        return value;
    } else {
        if constexpr (std::is_same_v<T, float>) {
            return std::bit_cast<T>(std::byteswap(std::bit_cast<std::uint32_t>(value)));
        } else if constexpr (std::is_same_v<T, double>) {
            return std::bit_cast<T>(std::byteswap(std::bit_cast<std::uint64_t>(value)));
        } else {
            return std::byteswap(value);
        }
    }
}

template<typename T>
T convert_endianness_runtime(T value, std::endian from, std::endian to) {
    if (from == to) {
        return value;
    } else {
        if constexpr (std::is_same_v<T, float>) {
            return std::bit_cast<T>(std::byteswap(std::bit_cast<std::uint32_t>(value)));
        } else if constexpr (std::is_same_v<T, double>) {
            return std::bit_cast<T>(std::byteswap(std::bit_cast<std::uint64_t>(value)));
        } else {
            return std::byteswap(value);
        }
    }
}
```

The implementation follows the pattern shown in the Hexi library fragment:
- If the source and target endianness are the same, return the value unchanged
- For floating-point types (float/double), use `std::bit_cast` to convert to an integer type, byteswap, then convert back
- For integral types, use `std::byteswap` directly
- The compile-time version uses `if constexpr` for optimization
- The runtime version uses regular `if` statements since the endianness parameters are runtime values

