Looking at the code fragments, I can see that `hexi::file_buffer` is used for file operations and `hexi::binary_stream` is used for reading/writing primitive types. Here's the implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/file_buffer.h>
#include <hexi.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <filesystem>

uint32_t read_uint32_from_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    // Create a file_buffer for reading
    hexi::file_buffer buffer(file_path.string().c_str());

    // Create a binary_stream from the file_buffer
    hexi::binary_stream stream(buffer);

    // Read the uint32_t value from the stream
    uint32_t value;
    stream >> value;

    return value;
}

void write_uint32_to_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path, uint32_t value) {
    // Create a file_buffer for writing
    hexi::file_buffer buffer(file_path.string().c_str());

    // Create a binary_stream from the file_buffer
    hexi::binary_stream stream(buffer);

    // Write the uint32_t value to the stream
    stream << value;
}
```

However, based on the error handling examples, it would be better to add proper error checking. Here's a more robust version:

```cpp
#include <hexi/file_buffer.h>
#include <hexi.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <filesystem>
#include <stdexcept>

uint32_t read_uint32_from_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    // Create a file_buffer for reading
    hexi::file_buffer buffer(file_path.string().c_str());

    // Check if file was opened successfully
    if (!std::filesystem::exists(file_path)) {
        throw std::runtime_error("File does not exist: " + file_path.string());
    }

    // Create a binary_stream from the file_buffer with error handling
    hexi::binary_stream stream(buffer, hexi::no_throw);

    // Read the uint32_t value from the stream
    uint32_t value;
    stream >> value;

    // Check if read was successful
    if (!stream) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Failed to read uint32 from file: " + file_path.string());
    }

    return value;
}

void write_uint32_to_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path, uint32_t value) {
    // Create a file_buffer for writing
    hexi::file_buffer buffer(file_path.string().c_str());

    // Create a binary_stream from the file_buffer with error handling
    hexi::binary_stream stream(buffer, hexi::no_throw);

    // Write the uint32_t value to the stream
    stream << value;

    // Check if write was successful
    if (!stream) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Failed to write uint32 to file: " + file_path.string());
    }
}
```

The key points from the code fragments:

1. `hexi::file_buffer` is used to handle file operations
2. `hexi::binary_stream` is created from the file_buffer to handle serialization
3. The `>>` and `<<` operators are used to read/write primitive types
4. Error handling can be done using `hexi::no_throw` and checking the stream state
5. The file path needs to be converted to a C-style string for the file_buffer constructor

The second version with proper error handling is recommended for production use.

