Looking at the code fragments, I can see that `hexi::file_buffer` is used for file operations, and `hexi::binary_stream` is used for reading typed data. Here's the implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/file_buffer.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <filesystem>

int32_t read_int32_from_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    hexi::file_buffer file(file_path);
    hexi::binary_stream stream(file);

    int32_t value;
    stream >> value;

    return value;
}

float read_float_from_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    hexi::file_buffer file(file_path);
    hexi::binary_stream stream(file);

    float value;
    stream >> value;

    return value;
}
```

However, based on the error handling examples, it would be better to add proper error checking. Here's a more robust version:

```cpp
#include <hexi/file_buffer.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <filesystem>
#include <stdexcept>

int32_t read_int32_from_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    hexi::file_buffer file(file_path);
    hexi::binary_stream stream(file);

    int32_t value;
    stream >> value;

    if (!stream) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Failed to read int32 from file: " + file_path.string());
    }

    return value;
}

float read_float_from_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    hexi::file_buffer file(file_path);
    hexi::binary_stream stream(file);

    float value;
    stream >> value;

    if (!stream) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Failed to read float from file: " + file_path.string());
    }

    return value;
}
```

The key points:
1. Create a `hexi::file_buffer` with the file path
2. Create a `hexi::binary_stream` using the file buffer
3. Use the stream extraction operator `>>` to read the typed values
4. Optionally check the stream state for error handling

The `hexi::binary_stream` automatically handles the proper byte ordering and type conversion when reading from the file buffer.

