Looking at the Hexi library structure and the provided code fragments, I can implement the string read/write functions. The library appears to use a prefixed format where the string length is written first, followed by the string data.

Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_writer.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_reader.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <string>

void write_string_to_stream(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_writer& writer, const std::string& str) {
    // Write the length of the string as a prefix
    writer.write(static_cast<uint32_t>(str.length()));

    // Write the string data
    if (!str.empty()) {
        writer.write(str.data(), str.length());
    }
}

std::string read_string_from_stream(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_reader& reader) {
    // Read the length prefix first
    uint32_t length = 0;
    reader.read(length);

    // Handle empty string case
    if (length == 0) {
        return std::string();
    }

    // Read the string data
    std::string result(length, '\0');
    reader.read(result.data(), length);

    return result;
}
```

This implementation follows the common pattern for prefixed string serialization:

1. **Writing**: First write the string length as a 32-bit unsigned integer, then write the actual string data.
2. **Reading**: First read the length prefix, then read that many bytes into a string.

The code handles edge cases like empty strings properly and uses the `write()` and `read()` methods that are typical for binary stream writers/readers in serialization libraries like Hexi.

