```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

void clear_buffer(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer) {
    buffer.clear();
}

void conditional_clear_buffer(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer) {
    buffer.conditional_clear();
}
```

The implementation is straightforward:

1. **`clear_buffer`**: Simply calls the `clear()` method on the buffer adaptor, which resets both read and write cursors to the beginning of the buffer.

2. **`conditional_clear_buffer`**: Calls the `conditional_clear()` method, which only clears the buffer when the read and write pointers are at the same position (indicating all data has been read).

From the code fragments, I can see that `buffer_adaptor` inherits from both `buffer_read_adaptor` and `buffer_write_adaptor`, and the `clear()` method calls `clear()` on both parent classes, while `conditional_clear()` checks if the read and write pointers are equal before calling `clear()`.

